---
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from "astro:i18n";
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import config from "@/config";

const locale = Astro.currentLocale ?? config.site.lang;
---

<Layout
  title={`AI-Native PRD | ${config.site.title}`}
  description="How to write PRDs for AI products: model behavior, tool boundaries, evaluation criteria, human-in-the-loop checkpoints, and failure modes."
>
  <Header />
  <Breadcrumb />

  <Main pageTitle="AI-Native PRD" class="app-prose">
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      Traditional PRDs describe static features. AI-native PRDs must also
      describe uncertainty, model behavior, evaluation logic, tool boundaries,
      fallback flows, and human-in-the-loop rules.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">What Changes in AI Products</h2>
    <p>
      In traditional software, the system does exactly what it is told. In AI
      products, the system reasons, generates, and sometimes gets things wrong.
      This changes how PMs write requirements: you define boundaries and
      guardrails, not just feature lists.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">The AI-Native PRD Checklist</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>User goal</strong> — What outcome does the user need? Not what the
        AI does, but what success looks like.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>AI capability boundary</strong> — What can the model do well? Where
        does it fail? Define the capability envelope explicitly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Input / output contract</strong> — What data goes in, what structured
        output comes out? Define schemas, not just "the AI suggests."
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Model behavior</strong> — Temperature, reasoning depth, deterministic
        vs. creative modes. Document expected behavior ranges.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tool permissions</strong> — What external tools can the AI call? Read-only
        or write? What are the blast radius limits?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Evaluation criteria</strong> — How do you measure whether the AI's
        output is good? Automated evals, human review, or both?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Human-in-the-loop checkpoints</strong> — When does the AI ask for
        approval? What happens if the human says no?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Failure modes</strong> — What are the 3-5 most likely failure scenarios?
        What does the user see? How does the system recover?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Observability and feedback loop</strong> — What gets logged? How do
        you collect signal to improve the system over time?
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Common Mistakes</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        Writing feature specs without defining the AI's capability boundary —
        the model cannot do everything, and pretending it can leads to broken
        products.
      </li>
      <li>
        Skipping failure modes — AI products fail in ways traditional software
        does not. If you don't design for failure, users hit dead ends.
      </li>
      <li>
        Treating the prompt as implementation detail — every prompt is a product
        decision with measurable outcomes.
      </li>
      <li>
        No evaluation plan — shipping without knowing how to measure quality is
        shipping blind.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">How I Use This</h2>
    <p>
      I use this checklist as the backbone for any AI product spec. Before
      writing wireframes or user stories, I fill out the capability boundary,
      failure modes, and HITL checkpoints. This forces clarity before design
      begins.
    </p>

    <div class="border-border mt-8 rounded-lg border p-6">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/prd-to-prototype")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          PRD to Prototype
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/agent-product-design")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Agent Product Design
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Playbook Index
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
